# Multi-Protocol Host Investigation & Threat Hunting Using Splunk

## Overview

This project demonstrates a host-centric threat hunting investigation using Splunk Enterprise and Zeek network telemetry.

Instead of focusing on a single protocol, this investigation correlates activity across DNS, HTTP, FTP, and SSH logs to develop a comprehensive profile of internal hosts. By aggregating protocol-specific events, security analysts can identify communication patterns, high-activity systems, and potential indicators of compromise across the network.

The investigation highlights how Splunk can be used to pivot across multiple Zeek log sources to build a complete understanding of host behavior.

---

## Objectives

- Identify the most active internal hosts
- Correlate activity across multiple network protocols
- Determine protocol usage per host
- Identify high-volume DNS clients
- Analyze HTTP communication patterns
- Investigate SSH activity between hosts
- Demonstrate host-centric threat hunting methodology
- Build a comprehensive behavioral profile for internal systems

---

# Environment

- Kali Linux
- Splunk Enterprise
- Zeek Network Security Monitor
- Network Traffic Dataset
- SPL (Search Processing Language)

---

# Investigation Workflow

The investigation followed a structured workflow.

1. Identify the most active internal hosts.
2. Correlate activity by log source.
3. Analyze HTTP communication.
4. Analyze DNS requests.
5. Analyze SSH connections.
6. Build a complete host activity profile.

---

# Investigation Queries

## Query 1 – Most Active Internal Hosts

```spl
index=main
| rex field=_raw "(?<ip>192\.168\.\d+\.\d+)"
| stats count by ip
| sort - count
| head 10
```

### Findings

The most active internal systems were identified by aggregating event counts across all available telemetry.

Top hosts included:

- 192.168.207.4
- 192.168.202.110
- 192.168.202.93
- 192.168.202.102
- 192.168.202.79

---

## Query 2 – Activity by Sourcetype

```spl
index=main
| rex field=_raw "(?<ip>192\.168\.\d+\.\d+)"
| stats count by ip sourcetype
| sort - count
```

### Findings

Correlation by sourcetype revealed which protocols generated the majority of activity for each internal host.

Observed protocol activity included:

- Zeek DNS
- Zeek HTTP
- Zeek FTP
- Zeek SSH

This allowed rapid identification of protocol-specific behavior across monitored systems.

---

## Query 3 – Top HTTP Source IPs

```spl
index=main sourcetype=zeek_http
| rex field=_raw "^\S+\s+\S+\s+(?<src_ip>\d+\.\d+\.\d+\.\d+)"
| stats count by src_ip
| sort - count
| head 10
```

### Findings

HTTP telemetry identified systems generating the highest volume of web traffic.

Most active hosts included:

- 192.168.202.110
- 192.168.202.102
- 192.168.202.79
- 192.168.202.96

This information can assist analysts when investigating browsing behavior, malware callbacks, or web-based command-and-control activity.

---

## Query 4 – Top DNS Source IPs

```spl
index=main sourcetype=dns.log
| rex field=_raw "^\S+\s+\S+\s+(?<src_ip>\d+\.\d+\.\d+\.\d+)"
| stats count by src_ip
| sort - count
| head 10
```

### Findings

DNS analysis highlighted the systems generating the highest number of domain lookups.

Top DNS clients included:

- 10.10.117.210
- 192.168.202.93
- 192.168.202.103
- 192.168.202.76

DNS monitoring provides valuable visibility into system communications and can assist with identifying suspicious external resolution attempts.

---

## Query 5 – Top SSH Source IPs

```spl
index=main sourcetype=zeek_ssh
| rex field=_raw "^\S+\s+\S+\s+(?<src_ip>\d+\.\d+\.\d+\.\d+)"
| stats count by src_ip
| sort - count
| head 10
```

### Findings

SSH analysis identified systems initiating the greatest number of secure shell connections.

Most active hosts included:

- 192.168.202.141
- 192.168.202.110
- 192.168.202.140
- 192.168.204.45

This information is useful when monitoring administrative access and identifying unusual remote login behavior.

---

# Key Findings

- Internal hosts displayed varying levels of protocol usage across the environment.
- DNS generated the highest overall activity.
- HTTP telemetry identified the primary web clients.
- SSH activity highlighted administrative communication between systems.
- FTP activity was observed for file transfer operations.
- Correlating multiple Zeek log sources provided a more complete understanding of host behavior than analyzing individual protocols independently.

